---
import BaseLayout from "../../components/BaseLayout.astro";
const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: "Home", path: "/" },
  { name: "Sources", path: "/sources/" },
];
const groups = [
  ["Primary clinical references.", "The DSM-5-TR for diagnostic criteria. The ICD-11 where international consistency matters. Official FDA medication labels for prescribing information."],
  ["Federal and academic health authorities.", "The National Institute of Mental Health for condition overviews and prevalence data. MedlinePlus from the National Library of Medicine for patient-facing explanations. The CDC for public health context. The American Psychiatric Association for clinical practice guidance."],
  ["Major medical centers.", "The Mayo Clinic, Johns Hopkins, and Cleveland Clinic for accessible, clinician-reviewed explanations of conditions and treatments."],
  ["Peer-reviewed literature.", "Papers indexed in PubMed, prioritizing meta-analyses, systematic reviews, and large studies published in respected journals."],
];
const authorities = [
  ["National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH)", "https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/topics"],
  ["MedlinePlus, U.S. National Library of Medicine", "https://medlineplus.gov/mentalhealthandbehavior.html"],
  ["American Psychiatric Association (APA)", "https://www.psychiatry.org/patients-families"],
  ["U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA)", "https://www.fda.gov/drugs"],
  ["Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)", "https://www.cdc.gov/mental-health/"],
  ["Mayo Clinic", "https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions"],
  ["Cleveland Clinic", "https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health"],
  ["PubMed, National Library of Medicine", "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/"],
  ["Cochrane Library", "https://www.cochranelibrary.com/"],
  ["988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (SAMHSA)", "https://988lifeline.org/"],
];
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Sources we cite | Shrinktionary"
  description="The categories of sources Shrinktionary treats as reliable: primary clinical references, federal and academic health authorities, major medical centers, and peer-reviewed literature."
  canonicalPath="/sources/"
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  keywords={["mental health sources","evidence-based","DSM-5-TR","NIMH","peer-reviewed"]}
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-prose px-5 py-14">
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-semibold text-ink">Sources we cite</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-[#1F2937] mt-5">Each Shrinktionary entry lists the specific sources that support its definition. These are the categories of sources we treat as reliable.</p>
    <dl class="mt-8 space-y-6">
      {groups.map(([term, desc]) => (
        <div>
          <dt class="font-semibold text-ink">{term}</dt>
          <dd class="text-[#1F2937] mt-1">{desc}</dd>
        </div>
      ))}
    </dl>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-ink mt-12">The organizations we rely on</h2>
    <p class="text-[#1F2937] mt-2">These are the primary, authoritative bodies behind our entries. Each link opens the organization's own site.</p>
    <ul class="mt-5 grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-8 gap-y-3">
      {authorities.map(([name, url]) => (
        <li>
          <a href={url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-watermelon underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-ink">{name}</a>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-ink mt-12">How we weigh a source</h2>
    <p class="text-[#1F2937] mt-2">Not all evidence carries the same weight, and we treat it that way. For diagnostic definitions, the DSM-5-TR and ICD-11 come first. For medications, we go to the official FDA label and the regulatory record. For how common a condition is, or how it's generally described, we lean on federal authorities like NIMH and MedlinePlus. When we summarize what treatments work, we prioritize systematic reviews and meta-analyses over single studies, and large, well-designed studies over small or preliminary ones. A single paper, a press release, or a striking finding that hasn't been replicated doesn't become a claim on this site.</p>
    <p class="text-[#1F2937] mt-4">When sources disagree, we say so rather than pretending the question is settled. And when the evidence is genuinely uncertain, we'd rather tell you it's uncertain than round it off into false confidence.</p>

    <p class="text-[#1F2937] mt-12">We don't cite blog posts, social media, or commercial health sites as primary sources. We don't cite ourselves. Each citation includes the title, publisher, and a direct link, and you'll find them at the bottom of every term.</p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
